{"ts":1346443420030,"silentsave":true,"restoring":false,"patch":[[{"diffs":[[1,"\r\n<div class=\"step container container-center\">\r\n    \r\n    <img src=\"http://placehold.it/256x256\" alt=\"Highlevel\">\r\n    <h1 class=\"superhero-type\">Lists <small>& </small>Tables</h1>\r\n    <h2 class=\"sidekick-type\">are high-level organizational elements</h2>\r\n    \r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<!--\r\n<div class=\"step container container-center\">\r\n    \r\n    \r\n    \r\n</div>\r\n<h1></h1>\r\n<h2></h2>\r\n<h3></h3>\r\n<h4></h4>\r\n<p></p>\r\n<small></small>\r\n<p><small></small></p>\r\n<span class=\"highlight\"></span>\r\n<span class=\"logo-type-purple\"></span>\r\n<span class=\"logo-type-blue\"></span>\r\n<span class=\"logo-type-green\"></span>\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n        <div class=\"span1\">\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n<div class=\"row\">\r\n        <div class=\"span9\">\r\n            <div class=\"container-left\">\r\n                <pre class=\"prettyprint linenums\">\r\n&lt;p&gt;...&lt;/p&gt;</pre>\r\n            </div>\r\n        </div>\r\n    </div>\r\n\r\nLists & Tables are high-level organizational elements\r\n\r\nA high-level element combines several simple or low-level elements to create a complex result\r\n\r\nFor example, a list is a container with a collection of information points, and a table a container with lots of sub-containers\r\n\r\nYou could create a list or table using lots of div and paragraph elements\r\n\r\nInstead, HTML provides us with semantic elements for both\r\n\r\nTo create a list, we use either a ordered or unordered list\r\n\r\nThe ordered list is denoted by <ol>, and is used for sequential information\r\n\r\nThe unordered list is denoted by <ul>, and is used for general information\r\n\r\nThe <ul> is used most commonly and works very well for navigation\r\n\r\nList items are denoted by <li>, and can contain multiple elements that relate to a single point of information\r\n\r\nThe <ul>’s list-style-type property defines the appearance of a bullet point, common values are circle, square, and none\r\n\r\nThe <ul>’s list-style-position property defines where the bullet point will appear, common values are outside and inside\r\n\r\nBy default, lists display vertically\r\n\r\nTo create a horizontal list, set the <li>’s display property to inline or inline-block\r\n\r\nTo control the spacing between list items, change the <li>’s padding or margin properties\r\n\r\nSometimes, our data is tabular, and for that we use a <table> element\r\n\r\nFor a long time, designers used tables across an entire website because they provided easy organization\r\n\r\nThis is now considered bad practice\r\n\r\nHTML tables are organized by row, then by column\r\n\r\nA table row is denoted by <tr>, and contains only column cells\r\n\r\nA table cell is denoted by <td>, and contains information, by default cells are left aligned\r\n\r\nA table body is denoted by <tbody> and contains all table content\r\n\r\nA table header is denoted by <thead> and is used for column labels\r\n\r\nTable cells inside the header are denoted by <th> and are by default center aligned and bold\r\n\r\nTable cells can span multiple rows with the rowspan attribute\r\n\r\nTable cells can span multiple columns with the colspan attribute\r\n\r\nBy default, tables are surrounded and sliced by borders\r\n\r\nThe border property affects all elements in a table and is on by default\r\n\r\nThe border-width property defines the size of the border\r\n\r\nThe border-style property defines the appearance of the border, common values are solid, dashed, & none\r\n\r\nThe border-color property defines the color of the border, set in hex, rgb, & rgba\r\n\r\nThe border property is a combination of border-width, border-style, & border-color\r\n\r\nBy default the border property affects all 4 sides\r\n\r\nTo set a border for a specific side, add -top, -bottom, -left, or -right after the word border in the property name\r\n\r\nThe <table>'s border-collapse property defines whether or not double borders in a table can merge into one\r\n\r\nMost table styling should be added to the table cells\r\n\r\nA special property of table cells is that they allow vertical alignment of content across a row\r\n\r\nEmpty table cells can create gaps in tables, to fix this use the special word “&nbzp;”\r\n\r\nTo avoid confusion in large tables, use the nth-child pseudo-selector to add alternating background colors\r\n\r\nThe background-color property defines the fill color of an element, common values are hex, rgb, rgba, and gradients\r\n\r\nTo select every even list item, use li:nth-child(even)\r\n\r\nFor our even rows, let's set the background-color to a simple hex #dddddd\r\n\r\nTo select every odd list item, use li:nth-child(odd)\r\n\r\nFor our odd rows, we’ll leave them as the default background-color\r\n\r\nYou can also use the :hover pseudo-selector to give a user feedback as they browse the table\r\n\r\nWhen we hover, let's set the background-color to #bbbbbb\r\n\r\n\r\n-->"]],"start1":0,"start2":0,"length1":0,"length2":4647}]],"length":4647}
